Final needle length, ranging between 40 and 160 mm, depended mainly on the amount of water and N stress experienced by trees during the growing season. The majority (greater than 90\%) of needle extension occurred during a 4 month period (October{\^{a}}{\texteuro}{\textquotedblleft}January) in spring and summer and the pattern of needle growth was affected only by water availability. Needle extension rates were negatively linearly correlated with the water stress integral (S{\"{I}}{\textasciicircum}, a temporal integration of the effects of both water and N availability on needle water potentials) for monthly periods during the growing season. Needle extension, was most sensitive to the S{\"{I}}{\textasciicircum} in mid-spring (October/November) when needles were elongating rapidly and still less than one-half grown.
